# Chatvioso UI Refactor Plan

## Purpose

This document defines the exact screen-by-screen plan for rebuilding the **Chatvioso UI from scratch**.

This is a **UI-only refactor plan** focused on:

- screen structure
- component breakdown
- UX priorities
- implementation order
- consistency across the product

The goal is to avoid random UI work and instead rebuild Chatvioso in a structured, scalable way.

---

# 1. Refactor Strategy

Refactor the product in this order:

1. design foundation
2. app shell
3. auth screens
4. conversation list
5. active chat screen
6. message composer
7. contact flows
8. group/chat details
9. settings/profile area
10. polish and responsive QA

This order matters because later screens depend on earlier UI foundations.

---

# 2. Phase 1 — Design Foundation

This phase creates the base system before rebuilding screens.

## Build in this phase

### 2.1 Design tokens
Create shared tokens for:

- colors
- spacing
- radius
- shadows
- typography
- z-index
- layout widths/heights

### 2.2 Base reusable UI components
Build the core primitives first:

- Button
- IconButton
- Input
- SearchInput
- Textarea
- Avatar
- Badge
- Tabs
- Dialog
- Drawer
- Dropdown
- Tooltip
- Skeleton
- Spinner
- Separator
- EmptyState
- ErrorState

### 2.3 Shared app primitives
Build shared non-feature-specific blocks:

- AppLogo
- PageHeader
- SectionHeader
- UserPresenceIndicator
- UnreadBadge
- StatusPill
- BackButton
- ScrollArea wrapper

## Done when

- visual language is established
- reusable primitives exist
- no screen needs to invent its own styling rules

---

# 3. Phase 2 — App Shell

This phase builds the structural shell for the app.

## Screens / layouts included

- AuthLayout
- MainChatLayout
- SettingsLayout
- Mobile navigation shell

## Build order

### 3.1 Global App Sidebar
Sidebar should include:

- logo
- main navigation
- chats shortcut
- contacts shortcut
- groups shortcut if relevant
- settings/profile shortcut
- current user area

### 3.2 Top Header / Topbar
Header should support:

- current view title
- contextual actions
- search trigger if needed
- mobile navigation trigger
- profile actions

### 3.3 Main Content Frame
Create the standard layout containers for:

- conversation list panel
- active conversation panel
- optional right details panel

### 3.4 Mobile shell
Define responsive behavior for:

- sidebar hidden behind drawer
- conversation list as first-level panel
- conversation view as second-level panel
- details panel as overlay/drawer

## UX rules

- app shell must feel stable
- height must work properly
- avoid double scroll bugs
- layout must not shift unexpectedly

## Done when

- desktop shell is usable
- mobile shell is defined
- all future screens can plug into this layout cleanly

---

# 4. Phase 3 — Auth Screens

Rebuild all auth-related UI.

## Screens included

- Login
- Register
- Forgot Password
- Reset Password

## Screen structure

### Left/right layout idea
Desktop may use:

- left: branding or value proposition panel
- right: auth card/form

Mobile should simplify to:

- centered single-column form

## Components to build

- AuthCard
- AuthFormHeader
- EmailField
- PasswordField
- AuthSubmitButton
- FormErrorMessage
- AuthSidePanel

## UX requirements

- clean and distraction-free
- strong hierarchy
- clear error messaging
- loading states on submit
- password visibility toggle
- proper spacing and labels

## Done when

- auth flow looks premium
- forms are fully consistent
- mobile auth experience is polished

---

# 5. Phase 4 — Conversation List Area

This phase rebuilds the left conversation panel.

## Main screen area

The conversation list panel should contain:

- panel header
- search
- optional tabs/filters
- recent conversations list
- pinned items if needed
- unread indicators
- empty state
- loading state

## Components to build

- ConversationPanelHeader
- ConversationSearch
- ConversationFilters
- ConversationList
- ConversationListItem
- PinnedConversationSection
- ConversationEmptyState
- ConversationListSkeleton

## Conversation list item must support

- avatar
- display name
- latest message preview
- time label
- unread badge
- active state
- muted state
- pinned state if needed
- online/offline indicator if relevant

## UX rules

- quick to scan
- active item must be obvious
- list density should feel balanced
- preview text should truncate properly
- unread state should stand out without looking noisy

## Done when

- conversation browsing feels premium
- list works on desktop and mobile
- all list states are covered

---

# 6. Phase 5 — Active Chat Screen

This is the most important phase.

## Main areas inside active chat panel

- conversation header
- messages area
- typing / status area
- composer

## 6.1 Conversation Header

### Must include
- avatar or group image
- title/name
- online/last seen/status text
- actions
- details panel trigger

### Components
- ConversationHeader
- ConversationHeaderMeta
- ConversationHeaderActions

## 6.2 Message Area

### Must support
- message groups
- own vs other messages
- timestamp handling
- day/date separators
- attachments
- system messages if any
- loading state
- empty state

### Components
- MessageList
- MessageGroup
- MessageBubble
- MessageMeta
- MessageStatus
- DateSeparator
- TypingIndicator
- MessageAttachmentPreview
- MessageListEmptyState
- MessageListSkeleton

## 6.3 Message Bubble Behavior

Each message bubble should support:

- sender alignment
- sender style variant
- time
- seen/delivered state if available
- text wrapping
- attachment rendering
- grouped appearance with nearby messages

## 6.4 Scroll Behavior

Must ensure:

- message area scrolls independently
- composer remains anchored
- loading older messages does not break layout
- no awkward jumpiness

## UX rules

- reading messages should feel effortless
- spacing between message groups should feel intentional
- own and other messages must be instantly distinguishable
- chat area must feel calm and uncluttered

## Done when

- message experience feels like a real product
- long conversations are readable
- empty/loading states feel polished

---

# 7. Phase 6 — Message Composer

The composer deserves its own phase because it is central to the app.

## Composer must support

- multiline text input
- send button
- attachment button
- disabled/loading states
- keyboard-friendly interaction
- nice focus state
- compact but premium layout

## Components

- MessageComposer
- ComposerToolbar
- ComposerTextarea
- ComposerActions
- SendMessageButton
- AttachmentTrigger

## UX rules

- send action must be obvious
- input should expand gracefully
- composer should not become visually bulky
- controls should be easy to use on mobile
- spacing must match premium chat apps

## Optional future-ready space
Keep architecture ready for:

- emoji button
- voice note
- file upload preview
- reply mode
- edit mode

Do not overbuild these now unless needed.

## Done when

- sending UI feels smooth
- mobile usability is strong
- composer integrates perfectly with chat layout

---

# 8. Phase 7 — Empty, Loading, and Error States

Before secondary screens, make the primary UX resilient.

## Required states to build

### Chat states
- no conversation selected
- no messages yet
- loading conversation
- failed to load conversation

### Conversation list states
- loading list
- no results
- no conversations

### Search states
- searching
- no matches
- error state

### Contacts/groups/settings
- empty base templates for each

## Rules

- never leave blank dead areas
- each state should be informative
- use helpful copy
- optionally include CTA buttons where useful

## Done when

- all major screens have robust fallback states

