# 13. Phase 12 — Responsive Refinement

Now refine every major UI area across breakpoints.

## Check and fix

### Desktop
- spacing
- panel widths
- multi-column comfort
- scroll behaviors

### Tablet
- collapsing panel behavior
- drawer transitions
- topbar action spacing

### Mobile
- panel switching
- touch target sizing
- composer usability
- chat readability
- header compactness

## Done when

- app feels intentionally designed for each breakpoint
- not just "shrunk down desktop UI"

---

# 14. Phase 13 — Interaction Polish

Add subtle product polish.

## Add carefully

- hover states
- active states
- focus states
- panel transitions
- skeleton shimmer
- subtle drawer/modal animation
- list hover polish
- button loading polish

## Avoid

- dramatic movement
- bouncy animation
- flashy unnecessary effects

## Done when

- interface feels smooth and intentional
- motion supports usability instead of distracting

---

# 15. Phase 14 — Accessibility Pass

Run a dedicated accessibility cleanup.

## Check all screens for

- semantic headings
- labels
- button accessibility
- keyboard navigation
- tab order
- focus visibility
- contrast
- aria labels where needed
- icon-only button clarity

## Done when

- product is usable beyond mouse-only interaction
- important states are not color-only

---

# 16. Phase 15 — Final Cleanup

Finish with a technical and visual cleanup pass.

## Cleanup tasks

- remove dead components
- remove old UI files
- remove duplicated styles
- align variant APIs
- unify spacing inconsistencies
- simplify over-complicated components
- normalize naming
- remove leftover old design patterns

## Done when

- codebase feels intentionally rebuilt
- no half-old / half-new UI remains

---

# 17. Recommended Implementation Order Summary

Follow this exact order:

1. design tokens
2. base UI components
3. shared primitives
4. app shell
5. auth screens
6. conversation list
7. active chat header
8. message list
9. message bubble/group system
10. composer
11. primary empty/loading/error states
12. contacts
13. details/group UI
14. settings/profile
15. search and support flows
16. responsive pass
17. accessibility pass
18. final cleanup

---

# 18. Definition of Done Per Screen

A screen is complete only if:

- layout is stable
- visual hierarchy is clear
- reusable components are used
- responsive behavior works
- empty/loading/error states exist
- keyboard/focus states exist
- no obvious duplicate code remains
- it matches the Chatvioso design system
- it feels production-ready

---

# 19. Strict Refactor Rules

While rebuilding screens, do not:

- redesign each screen independently
- use inconsistent spacing
- keep old messy structure just because it works
- create special-case UI components without good reason
- ignore mobile until the end
- skip empty/loading/error states
- create giant page-level files
- mix multiple design languages
- overcomplicate features before the core UX is solid

---

# 20. Final Refactor Mindset

For every screen, ask:

1. Is this simpler than before?
2. Is this more reusable than before?
3. Is this visually cleaner than before?
4. Is this more responsive than before?
5. Is this easier to maintain than before?
6. Does this feel like a real product?

If not, keep improving before marking the screen complete.
